# --- Database ---
DATABASE_URL=sqlite:///./data/stories.db

# --- LLM (OpenAI-compatible; Gemini is NOT supported) ---
OPENAI_API_KEY=
OPENAI_BASE_URL=https://api.openai.com/v1
DEFAULT_SUMMARY_MODEL_NAME=gpt-4o-mini
DEFAULT_GROUPING_MODEL_NAME=gpt-4o-mini
SUMMARY_MAX_OUTPUT_TOKENS=8192
GROUPING_MAX_OUTPUT_TOKENS=4096
SUMMARY_LLM_TEMPERATURE=0.2
GROUPING_LLM_TEMPERATURE=0.1

# --- RSS Feeds (comma-separated or JSON list) ---
# Examples:
#   RSS_FEED_URLS=https://feeds.bbci.co.uk/news/world/rss.xml,https://rss.nytimes.com/services/xml/rss/nyt/World.xml
#   RSS_FEED_URLS=["https://feeds.bbci.co.uk/news/world/rss.xml","https://rss.nytimes.com/services/xml/rss/nyt/World.xml"]
RSS_FEED_URLS=

# --- Scheduler ---
DEFAULT_RSS_FETCH_INTERVAL_MINUTES=30
MAX_ARTICLES_PER_INDIVIDUAL_FEED=15
RECLUSTER_HOUR_UTC=3
LIFECYCLE_TICK_HOURS=1
AUTO_ARCHIVE_DAYS=7
ARCHIVE_REVIVE_WINDOW_DAYS=30

# --- Scraper / Playwright ---
PLAYWRIGHT_USER_AGENT=Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/120.0.0.0 Safari/537.36
PLAYWRIGHT_TIMEOUT=60000
PLAYWRIGHT_PAGE_WAIT_MS=3000
SCRAPE_REQUEST_DELAY_SEC=1
USE_HEADLESS_BROWSER=True
# Leave empty to auto-detect ./scraper_assistant
PATH_TO_EXTENSION=

# --- Ports ---
MAIN_PORT=8800

# --- Summary prompts (optional overrides) ---
# The defaults are defined in app/config.py and used by app/grouping/summarizer.py.
#   DEFAULT_MAJOR_SUMMARY_PROMPT       — used for the initial event-level summary
#                                          and for full regenerations.
#                                          Placeholders: {event_name}, {article_texts}.
#   DEFAULT_SUMMARY_INCREMENTAL_PROMPT — used when 1+ new articles join an existing
#                                          event and the prior summary is updated.
#                                          Placeholders: {event_name}, {new_count},
#                                          {new_article_texts}, {prior_summary_json}.
# Uncomment + set to override. Keep the {{ ... }} double-braces around the inner
# JSON skeleton (and escape any other literal { or } as {{ or }}) so .format()
# still works at call time. The first call to summarize/regenerate will use
# whatever value is here. Note: prompts are read on process start, so after
# editing .env you'll need to restart `python -m app.cli serve` for the change
# to take effect.
#
# DEFAULT_MAJOR_SUMMARY_PROMPT=
# DEFAULT_SUMMARY_INCREMENTAL_PROMPT=

# --- Debug ---
DEBUG_LEVEL=standard

# --- Current working prompts (loaded from app/config.py; values shown here are the active fallbacks) ---
# Uncomment a line, edit, and copy to your .env to override. The prompts are read on
# process start (app/config.py: load_dotenv + os.getenv), so restart the server after editing.

# DEFAULT_MAJOR_SUMMARY_PROMPT="You are summarizing a collection of articles about {event_name} for a reader who skims many events quickly. Lead with the most recent and most significant developments, and treat older developments as supporting context.\n\nEach article carries a publish date and an importance score (0–1). Treat both as ranking signals: prefer more recent and higher-importance developments when deciding what leads the key_developments list and what is surfaced at the recent end of the timeline, so a long-running event stays current rather than weighting weeks of coverage evenly. Use these signals to choose emphasis only; keep every article in scope and report on the full set.\n\nReturn your answer as valid JSON using EXACTLY the structure below. Keep all output as plain JSON, and escape any internal quotes and newlines so the JSON stays valid.\n\n{{\n \"key_developments\": [\"Each item is a self-contained, scannable line that leads with the concrete development, written so a renderer can bold the opening phrase. Compare candidate developments against each other and select the most significant; lead with the strongest. Include up to 5 items, and keep each to roughly 25 words.\"],\n \"timeline_narrative\": [{{\"date\": \"<YYYY-MM-DD or phase label>\", \"text\": \"One short connective paragraph for this phase, written as causal prose. Keep it to roughly 60 words.\"}}],\n \"cross_source_synthesis\": {{\n  \"by_source\": [{{\"source\": \"<outlet>\", \"observation\": \"How this outlet covers the story differently — its unique angle, emphasis, or framing. Keep it to roughly 30 words.\"}}],\n  \"synthesis\": \"One closing paragraph reconciling the sources: note conflicts, consensus, or patterns in coverage. Keep it to roughly 80 words. When only one source exists, summarize its stance on its own terms.\"\n }},\n \"progressive_summary\": \"What the reader most needs to know right now — the latest material developments, written as full prose. Keep it to roughly 120 words.\",\n \"article_count\": <total number of articles analyzed>,\n \"feed_count\": <number of unique feeds>,\n \"date_range\": \"<earliest date> - <latest date>\"\n}}\n\nFormat each field to its job: parallel items as a list, connective reasoning as prose. Treat only genuine article content as input; skip scraped UI artifacts and boilerplate such as 'toggle caption' or navigation labels.\n\nArticles to analyze (each prefixed with source, date, and importance score):\n{article_texts}\n\nTwo rules govern everything above, applied as you generate: order timeline_narrative entries chronologically by date, oldest to newest (let the recency and importance signals decide which recent developments to surface, never the timeline's sort order); and base every statement strictly on the article texts provided, inventing no facts, sources, or conflicts.\n\nReturn the JSON now:"

# DEFAULT_SUMMARY_INCREMENTAL_PROMPT="You are updating an existing event summary for {event_name} with {new_count} new article(s) for a reader who skims many events quickly. You are given the prior summary (JSON below) and the new article(s). Incorporate the new material while preserving the established structure, and keep recent, significant developments at the front, with older items kept as context.\n\nEach new article carries a publish date and an importance score (0–1). Treat both as ranking signals: prefer more recent and higher-importance developments when deciding what leads the key_developments list and what is surfaced at the recent end of the timeline, so the summary stays current rather than weighting older coverage evenly. Use these signals to choose emphasis only; keep the full picture in scope.\n\nTasks:\n 1. key_developments: merge in the new milestones, compare all candidates against each other on significance, keep the most significant up to a total of 5, and lead with the strongest.\n 2. timeline_narrative: append new dated phase(s) in chronological order, and keep existing entries as they are unless the new articles update them.\n 3. cross_source_synthesis: add a by_source entry when a new outlet or a new angle/conflict appears, and refresh the synthesis whenever the overall picture changes.\n 4. progressive_summary: rewrite it to focus on what is new since the prior summary.\n\nReturn your answer as valid JSON using EXACTLY the structure below. Keep all output as plain JSON, and escape internal quotes and newlines.\n\n{{\n \"key_developments\": [\"Self-contained, scannable line that leads with the development, up to 5 items, roughly 25 words each.\"],\n \"timeline_narrative\": [{{\"date\": \"<YYYY-MM-DD or phase label>\", \"text\": \"Short connective paragraph for this phase, roughly 60 words.\"}}],\n \"cross_source_synthesis\": {{\n  \"by_source\": [{{\"source\": \"<outlet>\", \"observation\": \"How this outlet covers the story differently, roughly 30 words.\"}}],\n  \"synthesis\": \"Closing paragraph reconciling the sources, roughly 80 words.\"\n }},\n \"progressive_summary\": \"What is new since the prior summary, written as full prose, roughly 120 words.\",\n \"article_count\": <new total number of articles>,\n \"feed_count\": <number of unique feeds>,\n \"date_range\": \"<earliest date> - <latest date>\"\n}}\n\nFormat each field to its job: parallel items as a list, connective reasoning as prose. Treat only genuine article content as input; skip scraped UI artifacts and boilerplate.\n\nPrior summary:\n{prior_summary_json}\n\nNew article(s) to incorporate:\n{new_article_texts}\n\nTwo rules govern everything above, applied as you generate: keep timeline_narrative entries in chronological order, oldest to newest (let the recency and importance signals decide which recent developments to surface, never the timeline's sort order); and base every statement strictly on the prior summary and the new article texts, inventing no facts. Keep field lengths within the stated limits.\n\nReturn the JSON now:"
